INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '57de6dc6-5f47-4fdf-aaf8-d313bae836d5',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$postgresql_de Meets DynamoDB — Mapping Single-Table Design, GSI/LSI, and Capacity Modes$escape$,
  $escape$DynamoDB's single-table design collapses all entity types into one table, encoding relationships directly into composite `pk + sk` key strings — e.g. `USER#123` / `ORDER#456`. From a postgresql_de perspective, this is deliberately anti-normalized: what you'd split across `users`, `orders`, and a foreign key, DynamoDB merges into one row with a JSONB-like blob.

The `pk` (partition key) maps conceptually to the leading column of a PostgreSQL composite primary key; `sk` (sort key) is the second. GSIs (Global Secondary Indexes) let DynamoDB query non-PK attributes — the equivalent of `CREATE INDEX` on arbitrary columns. LSIs (Local Secondary Indexes) keep the same partition key but sort on a different attribute — analogous to `CREATE INDEX ON entities (pk, data->>'amount')`.

Capacity modes (provisioned RCU/WCU vs. on-demand) have no postgresql_de equivalent. PostgreSQL scales through PgBouncer connection pooling, `max_connections`, autovacuum tuning, and read replicas — throughput is managed at the infrastructure layer, not the table level.

When mirroring DynamoDB access patterns in postgresql_de, a polymorphic `entities` table with a `JSONB data` column plus targeted GIN/B-tree indexes delivers comparable query flexibility while retaining JOIN capability.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Mirroring DynamoDB single-table design in postgresql_de
CREATE TABLE entities (
  pk          TEXT        NOT NULL,  -- e.g. USER#123
  sk          TEXT        NOT NULL,  -- e.g. ORDER#456
  entity_type TEXT        NOT NULL,
  data        JSONB,
  created_at  TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT now(),
  PRIMARY KEY (pk, sk)
);

-- GSI equivalent: query across all entity types by date
CREATE INDEX idx_entities_type_created
  ON entities (entity_type, created_at DESC);

-- LSI equivalent: same PK, alternate sort on a data attribute
CREATE INDEX idx_entities_pk_amount
  ON entities (pk, ((data->>'amount')::numeric) DESC);$escape$,
