INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2614d693-2d9f-4349-9ce9-21834835ad93',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$PostgreSQL Replication — The synchronous_commit Dial and What Each Mode Actually Guarantees$escape$,
  $escape$PostgreSQL's streaming replication ships WAL segments from primary to standbys continuously. The consistency knob is `synchronous_commit`, with five levels: `off` (acknowledge before local flush — up to `wal_writer_delay` of data loss risk), `local` (flush locally, replicate async), `remote_write` (standby OS has received WAL), `remote_apply` (standby has applied — read-your-writes safe on hot standbys), and `on` (alias for `remote_write` in physical replication).

Replication slots pin WAL on the primary until each consumer catches up. A lagging slot fills `pg_wal` and can crash the primary — set `max_slot_wal_keep_size` as a hard cap and monitor `pg_replication_slots.confirmed_flush_lsn` vs `pg_current_wal_lsn()` for drift.

For lag-aware read routing, query `pg_stat_replication.replay_lag` on the primary before deciding whether to serve from a hot standby or fall back to primary.

Multi-leader isn't native PostgreSQL — EDB's BDR (built on pglogical) handles it with configurable `bdr.conflict_resolution` policies. Leaderless quorum writes don't exist in core PostgreSQL; Citus distributes shards but still routes through a coordinator.

`synchronous_standby_names = 'FIRST 1 (replica1, replica2)'` lets you require only a quorum subset to acknowledge, balancing availability against durability.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Inspect lag and sync state from the primary
SELECT
  application_name,
  sync_state,
  write_lag,
  flush_lag,
  replay_lag,
  pg_wal_lsn_diff(sent_lsn, replay_lsn) AS bytes_behind
FROM pg_stat_replication;

-- Elevate durability for a single critical transaction
SET LOCAL synchronous_commit = remote_apply;
INSERT INTO audit_log (event, actor) VALUES ('payment_confirmed', 'usr_42');
COMMIT; -- blocks until standby has replayed, not just received$escape$,
