INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f11676c9-2b4b-421e-8016-06abba2a9aca',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$PostgreSQL Connection Pooling — Sizing PgBouncer Before max_connections Kills You$escape$,
  $escape$Every PostgreSQL backend process costs ~5–10 MB of RAM. With the default max_connections = 100, a spike of 150 app threads will queue or outright reject connections. PgBouncer solves this by multiplexing thousands of client connections onto a small PostgreSQL-side pool.

Use transaction pooling (pool_mode = transaction) for stateless web workloads — it recycles a server connection the moment a transaction commits. Avoid session pooling unless your app uses SET LOCAL, advisory locks, or prepared statements, all of which are connection-scoped.

Pool sizing formula: default_pool_size ≈ (num_cores × 2) + effective_spindle_count. For a 4-vCPU Azure Flexible Server, that's ~10 server connections per database. Set max_client_conn to your total app thread ceiling (e.g. 500).

Monitor with SELECT count(*), wait_event_type FROM pg_stat_activity GROUP BY wait_event_type. A surge in Client wait events means PgBouncer's pool is exhausted — raise default_pool_size or shard across multiple PgBouncer instances. Never raise max_connections as a first response; you'll just shift the OOM problem to the OS.$escape$,
  $escape$[databases]
mydb = host=127.0.0.1 port=5432 dbname=mydb

[pgbouncer]
pool_mode = transaction
max_client_conn = 500
default_pool_size = 10
reserve_pool_size = 2
reserve_pool_timeout = 3
server_idle_timeout = 30
listen_port = 6432
auth_type = scram-sha-256$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
